# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Hotel Agrabad is one of the oldest hotels in the city.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The area hosts many businesses, and government offices including the art deco offices of M.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Ispahani Limited, the Jamuna Oil Company, BSTI divisional Office, Anti-Corruption commission etc.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Other streets in Agrabad include Access Road and Sabdar Ali Road.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The city's other commercial hubs on Strand Road and Sadarghat are located nearby.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The Chittagong Development Authority (CDA) was established in 1959 for urban planning.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] In the early 1960s, CDA created the 82-acre Agrabad CDA residential area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It envisioned the area housing government workers, whose offices would be located in Agrabad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] As Agrabad developed, properties near the Karnaphuli River were turned to business uses, creating the Agrabad Commercial Area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] In 1995, the Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE) opened in Agrabad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The CSE emerged as one of the twin stock markets of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Computerized transactions were introduced on the floor of the CSE in 1998.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] In 1999, the Bangladesh Securities and Exchange Commission enacted specific regulations for the CSE, including the CSE Automatic Transaction Regulation and the Chittagong Stock Exchange Investors Protection Fund Regulation.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Agrabad's average elevation is 0.42 metres (1 ft 5 in).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] As of 2020, the average high tide there is 2.51 metres (8 ft 3 in).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Since the early 1990s, the residential area has suffered regular inundation.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] As of 2018, the roads of the residential area are flooded at least waist deep for several hours twice a day during about a third of each month.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Once an affluent neighborhood, it has become a low rent area of absentee landlords.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Tidal flooding has also reached the Chattogram Maa-O-Shishu Hospital Medical College and the World Trade Center Chittagong in the commercial area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Many of Bangladesh's largest companies, as well as various multinational firms, have their headquarters or branches located in Agrabad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Some Islamic commercial banks are also located in Agrabad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] They include Islami Bank of Bangladesh Limited, Export Import Bank of Bangladesh Limited, Shahjalal Islami Bank Limited, Al-Arafah Islami Bank Limited.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Major foreign commercial banks located in Agrabad include Citibank NA, HSBC, Standard Chartered Bank, Commercial Bank of Ceylon, State Bank of India and National Bank of Pakistan.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] There are many Specialized development banks are Bangladesh Krishi Bank, BASIC Bank Limited, There are also located kinds of Non-bank financial institution, Insurance company, Telecommunication company and others multinational companies are located.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Chittagong Chamber of Commerce & Industry, The World Trade Center Chittagong (WTC Chittagong) etc. commercial building located in the Agrabad Commercial Area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Agrabad's 2nd economy hub in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The Ethnological Museum established in 1965, is the only ethnological museum in the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It offers the visitors the chance to acquaint with the lifestyles and heritage of various ethnic groups of the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The museum authority had collected rare elements used in the everyday lives of different ethnic groups, of which some had already become extinct while some were on the verge of extinction.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It contains four galleries and a small hall.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Three galleries of the museum feature diverse elements of twenty nine ethnic groups in Bangladesh, while the rest of the gallery displays the lifestyles of some ethnic groups of India, Pakistan and Australia.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The sculptures of the people of different ethnic communities and a piece of broken Berlin Wall attracts visitors, which close to display since 2017.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] People can get the impression of different festivals, livelihoods, and cultures of the communities from the murals set up at the hall room.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] These are reminiscent of the museum in the film *Planet of the Apes*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Around 200–300 people visit the museum every day.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Jamboree Park is the most visited stunning urban park located at SM Morshed Road at central Agrabad and visited by tourists and locals.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The park offers a dazzling view at night with several hundred lamps on its pool-like body of water and walkways.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Agrabad Deba *pool* (small body of water in Bengali) is about 14 acres human-made water reservoir is being this place in the Agrabad commercial area beside Sheikh Mujib Road since the last century.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The pool is a place for flyfishing, where it arranging fishing competition every year.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It was dug for the Bangladesh Railway and employees of the Port of Chittagong as well as the Chittagong city dwellers during the British period to carry out their daily chores and other activities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] After the water reservoir owned by the Bangladesh Railway.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Karnaphuli Shishu Park was a recreation park for children near Jamburee Park in Agrabad which is closed since August 2024.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Transport in Agrabad is similar to that of the city, Chittagong.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Several roads are present throughout the area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] There are various bus transport systems and taxi services, as well as smaller 'baby' or 'CNG' taxis, which are basically tricycle-structured motor vehicles.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] There are also traditional manual rickshaws, which are very common.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The Agrabad Access road and Sheikh Mujib road are a major arterial road, is the main way to access the area by motor vehicle and otherwise.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Those are considered a very busy and populated road, and though are currently 2-lane road.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Agrabad Access Road is a main commercial road located at Agrabad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It is extended to the south side, between Double Mooring Thana and Halishahar Thana.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The road started from Badamtali, and crossed Bepari Para, Shantibag, and Boropool.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] Sabdar Ali Road is a main commercial road located at Agrabad commercial area in central Agradad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] It is extended to the eastern side, beside Agrabad Access Road.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/agrabad] The road started from Badamtali and connected with Commerce College Road with surrounded to the total commercial area.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The **Asiatic Society of Bangladesh** is a non political and non profit research organisation registered under both Society Act of 1864 and NGO Affairs Bureau, Government of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The Asiatic Society of Bangladesh was established as the **Asiatic Society of East Pakistan** in Dhaka in 1952 by a number of Muslim leaders, and renamed in 1972.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Ahmed Hasan Dani, a noted Muslim historian and archaeologist of Pakistan played an important role in founding this society.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] He was assisted by Muhammad Shahidullah, a Bengali linguist.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The society is housed in Nimtali, walking distance from the Curzon Hall of Dhaka University, locality of Old Dhaka.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Asiatic Society of Bangladesh traces its origins to The Asiatic Society, which was founded by Sir William Jones in 1784.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Some of scholars of the Asiatic Society moved to Dhaka, capital of East Bengal, after the Partition of India.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Ahmad Hasan Dani, professor of history at the University of Dhaka, proposed the idea of establishing a Asiatic Society in Dhaka which was widely appreciated by scholars in Dhaka.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Asiatic Society of Pakistan was established on 3 January 1952 by Ahmad Hasan Dani, Abu Mohammed Habibullah, Abdul Halim, Abdul Hamid, Itrat Husain Zuberi, J.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] Turner, Khan Bahadur Abdur Rahman Khan, Muhammad Shahidullah, Sayed Moazzem Hossain, Serajul Huq, Sheikh Sharafuddin, Syed Muhammed Taifoor, and W.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The society modeled after The Asiatic Society in Kolkata is managed by a 17 member executive committee which has a two year term.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] In September 2013, the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh published a junior version of Banglapedia.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The Asiatic Society of Bangladesh in November 2020 cancelled the grant of two professors at the University of Dhaka after it found evidence of plagiarism in their work.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/asiatic-society-of-bangladesh] The Asiatic Society Heritage Museum is located in Old Dhaka.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-accreditation-board] The **Bangladesh Accreditation Board** is an autonomous government agency responsible for providing accreditations to Bangladeshi laboratories, testing centres, and certification bodies.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-accreditation-board] The Bangladesh Accreditation Board was established on 6 September 2006 by the government of Bangladesh through an act of parliament.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-accreditation-board] The United Nations Industrial Development Organization hired a French-Canadian consultant, Ned Gravel, to improve the practices in the board and this was done under a project funded by the European Union.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-accreditation-board] In 2015 the board signed an agreement with the Thai Industrial Standard Institute to improve trade ties between Bangladesh and Thailand.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-accreditation-board] The chairman of Western Marine alleged that the accreditation issued by the board is sometimes not accepted in other countries.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The **Bangladesh Computer Council** (**BCC**) is a statutory government organization operating under the Information and Communication Technology Division of the Ministry of Posts, Telecommunications, and Information Technology of the government of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Its headquarters are situated in Agargaon, Dhaka, Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It was initially known as the *National Computer Committee* (NCC) in 1983 and transformed into the *Bangladesh Computer Council* through Act No.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Since its inception, the BCC has been an important advocate for the country's technological development, specifically in information and communications technology (ICT).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In collaboration with government organizations in Bangladesh, this organization is responsible for developing national ICT plans, strategies, and policies, empowering Digital Bangladesh, implementing e-government, and collaborating with various government organizations and private sector partners.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They also set ICT standards and specifications, develop ICT infrastructure, provide advice on IT technology utilization and security measures, identify issues related to national cyber security and cybercrimes, and investigate, remediate, prevent, and suppress these issues.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC has undertaken numerous projects to improve the country's ICT infrastructure, such as *BanglaGovNet*, *Info-Sarker Phases II* and *III*, *Connected Bangladesh*, and others, many of which have already been completed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It has also significantly contributed to human resource development by providing training to thousands of individuals, including the disabled, transgender and third-gender communities, and women entrepreneurs.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 2022, the BCC organized the 45th Annual International Collegiate Programming Contest World Final in Dhaka, Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The organization has received several awards and recognitions for its achievements in promoting ICT in Bangladesh, such as the *WITSA award*, *WSIS Winner Prize*, *ASOCIO Digital Government Award*, *Open Group President Award*, *Public Administration Award 2017, etc*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The government of Bangladesh established the *National Computer Committee* (NCC) in 1983.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Nevertheless, the *National Computer Board* (NCB) took over the role of the NCC in 1988.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 1989, the "*Bangladesh Computer Council Ordinance*" was put into effect.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The following year, the National Parliament enacted Act No.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] 9, "*Bangladesh Computer Council Act, 1990"*, which transformed the National Computer Board into a statutory body under the name "Bangladesh Computer Council".
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC continued to function under the President's Secretariat until 1991.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 1991, this organization was placed under the Ministry of Science and Technology, which later became the Ministry of Science and Information and Communication Technology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Over the years, the BCC has evolved and expanded its scope of activities to meet the growing demands of the ICT sector.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 2011, the BCC was placed under the newly created Information and Communication Technology Division of the Ministry of Posts, Telecommunications and Information Technology of the government of Bangladesh (GoB).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] These responsibilities encompass a wide range of initiatives and projects aimed at contributing to the development of the ICT sector in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC has a robust organizational structure that allows it to handle its wide range of responsibilities and initiatives efficiently.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Executive Director is the highest-ranking official and is responsible for overseeing all operations of this organization.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Under the Executive Director, there are three primary Divisions, each headed by a Member, and each of these divisions further consists of several subdivisions, each overseen by a Director.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Technical Division handles technical matters such as data center operations, Certifying Authority activities, Object Identifier (OID) operations, and government-level ICT support services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Policy, Strategy, and Development Division is responsible for formulating and overseeing information technology policies, strategies, and development efforts.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Capacity Development and Human Resources Division is in charge of capacity building and human resource functions for the ICT sector.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has established seven regional offices in different parts of the country, which collaborate with local governments and non-governmental organizations to develop and implement national information and technology policies, strategies, and plans.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] These offices also assist in the implementation of e-government initiatives at the local level.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Furthermore, They provide ICT training, develop ICT curricula, and support human development by hosting workshops, seminars, and online practice and e-learning activities in their respective regions with the collaboration of the local ICT industry.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC's Council Committee is a group of 12 individuals from various government departments.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The council is in charge of supervising and directing the council's operations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC's CA Operations and Security serves as the sole official Certifying Authority of the government of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Its duties entail overseeing CA operations, enforcing regulations, and managing Electronic Signatures and a secure repository of electronic signature certificates.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This guarantees a reliable infrastructure for secure electronic transactions and communications in Bangladesh while providing secure digital certificates, web-based SSL certificates, PKI tools, and e-signatures to government organizations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The National Network Operation Center (NOC) was formed in 2014 to operate and maintain the e-government Network.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It focuses on network security, planning, research and development, operation, upgrade, and maintenance of nationwide government networks.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] NOC provides internet, intranet, extranet, and government video conference networks for the President, Prime Minister, Ministries, Bangladesh Secretariat, and field administration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] NOC provides consultation with other government organizations in preparing network standards and specifications.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Currently, it is providing network operation and maintenance services in 18,834 government offices up to the upazila level.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It also monitors the network connectivity of 2600 unions under the national priority project named ‘Info Sarker-3’.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC operates a *Tier III-certified National Data Center* in Bangladesh that offers a comprehensive range of services to government organizations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This data center provides secure and reliable cloud services and the storage and management of digital data for various government agencies and organizations in the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The National Data Center offers a range of Cloud computing services, including Elastic Cloud Server (ECS), Image Management Services (IMS), Elastic Volume Service (EVS) for Cloud Storage, Volume Backup Service (VBS), and Cloud Server Backup Service (CSBS) for Cloud Backup.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In addition, it provides Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), Elastic IP (EIP), Elastic Load Balancer (ELB), and Virtual Firewall (VFW) for Cloud Network Services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Other services offered are virtual Private Servers, Load Balancing, Email Service, Web Hosting, Backup, and Colocation Services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] A dedicated security team is in place to monitor and handle any security incidents that may arise.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This wing facilitates the testing (functional, performance, and security) of all software, applications, and mobile apps developed and procured by the government entity for e-government service delivery.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It also conducts hardware testing, ensures quality assurance, and coordinates software certification.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC is conducting research and development work on emerging technologies in the field of information technology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It formulates appropriate standards for implementing e-governance and software and hardware for capacity development, and it works on interoperability.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It establishes and manages appropriate centers or systems to develop the innovative power of potential ICT graduates.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It works on the development of IT personnel according to domestic and international markets and the commercialization of ICT.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC assists the government of Bangladesh in policy formulation, implementation, and monitoring.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This organization coordinates with government institutions, conducts studies and surveys, and develops management information systems to address national needs.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC provides ICT-related consultancy services to government and public organizations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] These services include requirements analysis for hardware and software, technical specification preparation, requirement analysis for automation, tender document preparation, and tender evaluation for government organizations with e-government empowerment initiatives.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Additionally, they provide on-demand websites and software development.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Furthermore, BCC offers ICT professional recruitment assistance.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC provides a crucial condemnation service for computers and related equipment, *ensuring proper identification and removal of outdated, obsolete, or non-functional hardware* for all government offices in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This service encourages responsible electronic waste disposal and the adoption of advanced technologies.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC is the country Registration Authority (RA) for Object identifiers (OIDs).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They received approval from the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) on July 30, 2012, to function as the country's RA.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] As the RA, this organization is responsible for allocating and managing OIDs within the country's OID allocation structure, which starts with country `OID 2.16.50`.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC oversees OID registration, ensures compliance, approves OIDs for the global repository, collaborates with ITU-T, defines valid objects, and assists OID users.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] As the country's RA, this organization facilitates a secure PKI and other IT initiatives.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Bangladesh e-government Computer Incident Response Team, also known as the National Computer Emergency Response Team of Bangladesh, is responsible for preventing and responding to cyber security threats within the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They work closely with international partners to ensure the safety of Bangladesh's cyberspace.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Their duties include receiving reviews, responding to computer security incidents, conducting research and development, and providing guidance on security threats and vulnerabilities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Additionally, they assist government organizations, financial organizations, law enforcement agencies, academia, and civil society in improving overall cyber security.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They also provide the necessary support to the 'Digital Security Agency'.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BGD e-GOV CIRT offers a range of essential services, including incident handling, digital forensics, cyber security training, threat intelligence, IT audits, cyber sensors, risk assessment, and awareness building.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] These services help organizations identify and respond to security incidents, evaluate potential security gaps, and build awareness about the importance of cyber security.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The government of Bangladesh has developed a National Enterprise architecture framework called the *Bangladesh National Digital Architecture Framework* based on leading standards, practices, and frameworks like Open Group's TOGAF 9.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This framework has been customized to meet the specific requirements and strategic objectives of the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] It consists of various key components that aim to establish the *Bangladesh National Enterprise Architecture Framework*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Such a component is the *eGovernment Interoperability Framework,* which ensures seamless integration and communication across different government departments and agencies.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Mobile Service Delivery Platform defines the architecture and standards for efficient mobile service delivery.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The National e-Service Bus acts as a middleware application or platform, facilitating the integration of e-services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC offers various training courses and programs, as well as job fairs, workshops, seminars, and programming competitions nationwide.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They also provide specialized training and events for disadvantaged communities, including the disabled and third-gender communities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Women entrepreneurs can also access various training opportunities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] To satisfy the rising demand in both the national and international job markets, BCC maintains an ICT training institute called BKIICT that provides a variety of ICT-related programs, including standard certification courses, diplomas, and post-graduate diplomas.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The institute also provides customized courses for government officials to improve their ICT skills and efficiency.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Besides, BKIICT conducts aptitude tests for ICT candidates applying for jobs in various government departments and organizations on behalf of those institutions.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They also conduct computer proficiency tests and provide lab rental services according to government requirements.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC's Bangladesh ICT-Engineers Examination Center, known as BD ITech, is responsible for the annual administration of the Information Technology Engineers Examination (ITEE) in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The ITEE is an internationally recognized information technology examination developed by Japan's Information Technology Promotion Agency (IPA).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This exam applies to both IT and non-IT professionals and graduates, and their knowledge and skills in this field can get international recognition.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Since 2013, BD-iTech has been entrusted by the Japanese government to conduct, implement, and certify ITEE exams in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC is conducting various national-level projects to improve the country's ICT infrastructure.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC has made significant contributions to ICT human resource development.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC and its various projects have trained over 2,36,000 individuals, including 187,200 males and 46,800 females, in various ICT skills until April 3, 2023.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Notably, from 2010 to 2022, BKIICT and 7 regional centers trained 36,000 individuals in diploma/PGD and short-term courses, preparing them for global employment opportunities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has also empowered teachers and students, with 7,890 teachers trained as master trainers and 112,189 students receiving Basic ICT training.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The council has provided training in emerging technologies like artificial intelligence (AI), the internet of things (IoT), blockchain, robotics, big data, medical scribe, and cyber security to government employees, educational institution teachers, entrepreneurs, and IT professionals.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has partnered with esteemed organizations such as Coursera, Facebook, and the National University of Singapore to enrich the training landscape in the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Moreover, this organization has set up an assessment and certification platform to foster skilled manpower development and further fuel the growth of the IT industry in Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Bangladesh Computer Council has been actively involved in the development of ICT infrastructure in Bangladesh to realize the Digital Bangladesh vision.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Their projects have been instrumental in the implementation of Digital Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] One of their most significant contributions is the expansion of the ICT Tower (formally known as the BCC Tower) to accommodate various important institutions related to ICT.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The building has been transformed into a "Center of Excellence" for all ICT-related government work.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The organization established Union Information and Service Centers (UISCs) through solar power in various unions without electricity, which were later renamed Union Digital Centers (UDCs).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They have also established Digital Centers like UISC at various offices in different upazilas across the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This organization has set up computer labs and smart classrooms in different educational institutions.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They have also established cybercenters at various universities and colleges.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Moreover, BCC has set up the National Data Center (Tier III), providing uninterrupted services to various government offices.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Disaster Recovery Center located in Jessore has been established, along with the 7th largest National Data Center (Tier-IV) Center in the world at Bangabandhu Hi-Tech City, Kaliakair, Gazpur.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has established a nationwide government network connectivity backbone under different projects, providing high-speed internet connections through optical fiber cable and the latest technology in video conferencing in several government offices across the country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Apart from this, the organization has set up Agricultural Information and Communication Centers and Telemedicine Centers.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They have also established WiFi networks in the Bangladesh Secretariat and ICT Tower and virtual private network (VPN) connectivity in the Bangladesh Police.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] At present, the process of providing connectivity to the unions in remote areas is underway under the *Connected Bangladesh* project.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has connected India, Nepal, Bhutan, and Bangladesh by optical fiber cable to increase data exchange capacity.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This organization has set up a 50-meter-high self-supported tower under the project entitled ‘*Digital Island Moheskhali*’ to introduce high-speed internet service.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] They have also set up an IP camera-based surveillance system to make Sylhet a "*Safe City*" under the "Digital Sylhet City" project.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] BCC has an idea fab lab, a specialized network lab, a software and hardware quality testing lab, a digital forensic lab, a cyber range, and a cyber defense training center.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] These labs are facilitated with world-class, advanced devices and technology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In addition, this organization has deployed cyber-sensor technology on various critical information infrastructures.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] As information technology continues to advance, it is crucial to establish standards that can enhance the accessibility of the Bengali language in the field of information technology, ensuring its ease of use for everyone.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The responsibility of promulgating these standards lies with the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI), while the task of technical drafting and declaration is carried out by the BCC.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The organization has already developed several standards and simultaneously modernized the existing ones.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Due to lack of coherence and synergy between vendors and technologists, these standards were largely never widely accepted nor recognized by international bodies.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Later, versions of standards such as BSCII in essence rubber stamped Unicode encoding scheme.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] An official order to mandatorily install a keyboard layout package kit in 2018 spawned furor over multiple fronts.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC organized the 'National Children and Youth Programming Contest 2018' to nurture the interest of children and adolescents in information technology education.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Students from different schools across the nation participated in this competition, which concluded with an award ceremony at the BCC auditorium on 30 October 2018.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] On February 22, 2020, the National Collegiate Programming Competition (NCPC) organized by the BCC was held at the Military Institute of Science and Technology (MIST) in Dhaka, Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Teams from different public and private universities took part in the event.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC held the National ICT Competition for Youth with Disabilities on November 21, 2020, with different contestants from various regions.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The competition was held at regional offices, including the head office in Dhaka.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The BCC and South Korea organized the 'iDEATHON' contest to promote startup entrepreneurs in Bangladesh in 2020.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The top 5 startups were awarded prestigious titles, and 10 entrepreneurs from the winning startups received a 6-month training program in South Korea, enhancing their expertise and capabilities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The competition aimed to advance the country's startup ecosystem.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The iDEA project under the BCC organized the 'Bangabandhu Innovation Grant-2021' to encourage young entrepreneurs and startups in honor of the Golden Jubilee of Independence and Mujib Year.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Startups and innovators from different countries, including Bangladesh, participated in the event.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The winning startup is awarded a grant of USD 100,000.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] On the auspicious occasion of 'Sheikh Russell Day 2021,' the Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina inaugurated a distribution program for 600 laptops to 600 disabled persons trained in ICT by the "Empowerment of Persons with Disabilities (PWD) including NDD through ICT" project under the BCC.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The fourth Bangladesh Robot Olympiad 2021 was organized in collaboration with the Information and Communication Technology Division, Dhaka University’s Department of Robotics and Mechanical Engineering, the Bangladesh Open Source Network, and the Bangladesh Computer Council.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Despite the challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic, Bangladesh actively participated in the Global IT Challenge 2021 for Youth with Disabilities.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The event, held online from South Korea, witnessed outstanding performances from four contestants representing Bangladesh, who were recognized with four prizes, including the esteemed Best Award (1st place).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Artificial Intelligence for Bangla’ Competition 2021 aimed to encourage university students, researchers, and developers to explore the Bengali language and technology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The competition sparked enthusiasm and increased interest in working with Bengali language-related AI and information technology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The National High School Programming Competition (NHSPC), organized by the BCC in 2021, encourages 6th–12th grade students in high schools, colleges, and madrasas to explore computer programming.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The aim is to increase computer programming's popularity among young students.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The 5th National Girls Programming Competition 2021 is jointly organized by the ICT Division, the Bangladesh Computer Council, and the Department of Computer Science and Engineering at Daffodil International University.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] Female students from various universities across the country participated in this competition.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The 45th Annual International Collegiate Programming Contest World Finals took place in Dhaka, Bangladesh, from November 6 to November 11, 2022.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The event was organized in partnership with the ICT Division of Bangladesh, the ICPC Foundation, the Bangladesh Computer Council, and the University of Asia Pacific.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] To motivate the students more in ICT and programming and to help them test their programming skills at a national level, the ICT Division of Bangladesh and Bangladesh Computer Council are jointly organizing the National High School Programming Contest 2022 with the slogan ‘জানুক সবাই দেখাও তুমি’.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Innovation Design and Entrepreneurship Academy (iDEA) Project of the BCC was runner-up in the Public-Private Partnership (PPP) category of the 2020 WITSA Global ICT Excellence Awards.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 2020, the e-recruitment platform of BCC received this award under the e-Employment category at the 9th annual WSIS Winner Prizes for Recruitment Process Management as a Shared Service for Government Agencies of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] In 2019, BCC received the *WSIS Champion Prize* for the *Development of National ICT Infra-Network for Bangladesh Government (Info-Sarker) Project*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The *Info-Sarker Phase 3* project of the BCC has been recognized with the esteemed ICT sector award *ASOCIO 2018 Digital Government Award* by the Asian-Oceanian Computing Industry Organization (ASOCIO).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] During the Asia Pacific Council for Trade Facilitation and Electronic Business Summit 2017, the BCC's *Info-Sarker Phase 3* initiative also won the *E-Asia 2017 Award*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The *4-Tier National Data Center (4TDC) Project* of the BCC was awarded the *DCD APAC Award 2019* in the Data Center Construction Category.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Bangladesh Computer Council received the '*Open Group President Awards 2018*' in the category of innovation for their work in developing the *Bangladesh National Enterprise Architecture* (BNEA) and *e-government Interoperability Framework* (e-GIF).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] This achievement was recognized for its contribution to making government information and services interoperable, ultimately supporting the goal of establishing a "Digital Bangladesh" by the year 2021.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Bangladesh Computer Council has been awarded "The Open Group President's Award" in the category of "Architecture Enabled Government Transformation" for the e-recruitment system in 2019.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-computer-council] The Hon'ble Prime Minister presented the Public Administration Award 2017 to the Bangladesh Computer Council in recognition of their significant contribution to public service.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The origins of the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI) can be traced back to the mid-20th century during the period of East Pakistan.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In 1955, a regional branch of the Central Testing Laboratories (CTL) was established in Dhaka to assess the quality of imported and domestically produced goods.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] This was followed by the establishment of a regional office of the Pakistan Standards Institution in Dhaka in 1957, and the creation of the Certification Marks Inspectorate in Chittagong in 1963 to regulate industrial product certification.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Following Bangladesh's independence in 1971, the Bangladesh Standards Institution (BDSI) was formed as the country's national standards body.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It became a member of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1974.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In an effort to consolidate standards development, testing, and certification functions, the government enacted Ordinance No.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] XXXVII of 1985, merging BDSI and CTL to form the present-day Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution's scope was further expanded in 1995 with the merger of the Department of Agricultural Grading and Marking.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Earlier, in 1982, the Standards of Weights and Measures Ordinance was promulgated to implement the metric system across the country, a function now overseen by BSTI.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI operates under the Ministry of Industries and serves as the national authority for standardization, conformity assessment, and metrology.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Over the years, it has undergone significant modernization.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A National Metrology Laboratory was established with financial and technical assistance from the European Union, NORAD, UNIDO, and the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's laboratories—covering physical, chemical, and microbiological testing—have received accreditation from the National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories (NABL) of India.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its product certification scheme is accredited by the National Accreditation Board for Certification Bodies (NABCB) of India.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Management System Certification (MSC) program has also been accredited by both Norwegian Accreditation and the Bangladesh Accreditation Board (BAB).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In recent years, BSTI expanded its infrastructure with the inauguration of a modern testing facility in Khulna on 21 November 2023, followed by the opening of a ten-story center in Chittagong's Agrabad Commercial Area on 28 June 2025.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Chittagong facility, equipped with advanced laboratories, aims to bolster the region's role as a major port and industrial hub by strengthening BSTI's capabilities in product testing, certification, and trade facilitation.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is the national standards body of Bangladesh, responsible for formulating and issuing Bangladesh Standards (BDS) for products, services, and processes.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Since its establishment, BSTI has developed over 4,000 standards to ensure quality, safety, and compliance.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It certifies products that meet national standards by issuing a Certification Mark (CM) licence, valid for three years, following thorough factory inspections and laboratory testing.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Use of the BSTI certification mark is restricted to licensed manufacturers.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Currently, 315 products require mandatory CM licences for domestic production, distribution, and sale, while 79 imported items need BSTI clearance under the country's import policy.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's Metrology Division regulates packaged commodities under the *Package Commodity Registration Rules 2021* and calibrates weighing and measuring devices to ensure adherence to the International System of Units.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution also provides laboratory testing and calibration services to industries, markets, government offices, and individuals.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its monitoring activities include market surveillance, mobile courts, and random sampling from markets and factories to combat substandard or counterfeit goods.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Additionally, BSTI represents Bangladesh in international and regional standards organizations and promotes public awareness of quality standards and consumer rights.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is an autonomous agency of the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It operates its activities under the *Bangladesh Standards & Testing Institution Act - 2018*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A counsel of 37 members is the decision-making body of the institution.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Minister for the Ministry of Industries is the chairperson of the counsel.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The encyclopedia's chief editor is Sirajul Islam.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Over 1450 writers and specialists in Bangladesh and abroad helped create the entries.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] *Banglapedia* has over 5,700 entries in six editorial categories, each of which is overseen by an expert editor, as well as over 2,000 single and four-colour illustrations and 2,100 cross-references.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The project was funded by the Government of Bangladesh, private sector organizations, academic institutes and UNESCO.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Though its original budget was 800,000 taka (roughly US$10,000), the Asiatic Society eventually spent 80 million taka (roughly US$1 million) on the project.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Despite controversies over entries on the Bangladesh Liberation War and indigenous people, both the Bengali and English versions became popular upon publication.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The *Banglapedia* project originated when the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh was working on a three-volume study titled *History of Bangladesh, 1704-1971* in 1991.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The editors felt the need for a standard desk reference, as that project progressed laboriously, culling facts from various libraries.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The idea finally led to a concept paper prepared by Sirajul Islam and his colleagues and submitted to the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh in early 1994.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The *Banglapedia* project was formally adopted on 19 February 1997, and Islam was appointed project director and chief editor.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] As the head of the Project Implementation Committee, his task was to plan and manage the project funding.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] In 1996, some three dozen committees were formed with three to four people in each committee to recommend the entries.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Twenty-seven thousand entries were proposed, requiring a 20-volume compendium.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Because of financial constraints, the number of entries was cut down to around 6,000.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The project officially took off in 1998.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] When the project began, the Society had only eight hundred thousand taka in its coffers for the project.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] *Banglapedia* raised further contributions from universities, banks, multinational companies, international organisations and even private individuals.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A pool of agencies, including UNESCO, the University Grants Commission, universities, financial institutions and NGOs initially financed the project, which was completed at a cost of taka 80 million.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Education Ministry funded about 74% of the cost, while 26% of the fund came mostly from universities and banks.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Before direct sales started on 3 January 2003, 4,000 copies of the English version and all but 250 copies of the Bengali version were sold in advance out of the initial print of 5,000 copies for each versions.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] For an additional run of 10,000 prints people waited in queues outside the Asiatic Society office on the day of the release, and sales continued until 9:30 in the evening.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A total of 4,500 sets of the Bengali version and 2,500 of the English version were sold on the day of release.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The first attempt to compile a Bengali encyclopedia was undertaken by Felix Carey (1786–1822), who was the son of Reverend William Carey (1761–1834) of Serampore and the first lexicographer of the Burmese language.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] In 1819, he began the translation of the fifth edition of Encyclopædia Britannica, naming it *Vidyarthabali*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] From October 1819 till November 1820 the book was printed by Felix Carey every month in 48-page installments.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Thus completed, the first part of *Vidyarthabali* was compiled into the 638-page *Vyabachchedvidya*, the first book on anatomy and surgery in Bengali.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Work on the second part, *Smritishastra*, which was largely on jurisprudence, then began.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] But Carey died after only two 40-page installments were printed in February and March 1821.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] It was followed by Maharaja Kalikirshna Dev Bahadur's (1808–1974) *Sankshipta Sadvidyabali* (1833), a concise encyclopedia.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Then came Raja Radhakanta Deb's *Sabdakalpadrum* (1822–1858), a Sanskrit encyclopedic dictionary in eight parts.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Next was Rajkrishna Ray (1849–1894) and Saratchandra Dev's (1858-unknown) joint work *Bharatkosh*, the first Bengali encyclopedia laid-out in alphabetical order (1880–1892) published in three volumes.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] After the independence of Pakistan and the partition of Bengal in 1947, there have been more attempts to compile and publish an encyclopedia.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The first was a project to produce a Bengali adaptation of *Columbia Viking Desk Encyclopedia* by Franklin Book Programs Inc., undertaken in 1959 and aborted ten years later.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The unfinished papers were compiled into four unequal volumes as *Bangla Vishvakosh* (1972) with Khan Bahadur Abdul Hakim as the chief editor.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The encyclopedia's editors intended to cover the rise of the Bengal Delta on the physical plane, and its evolution to date, and the changing features of the formation of the delta's *janapada* or human settlements on the human plane.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The latter includes the rise and fall of kingdoms, invasions from within and beyond and their implications, dynastic rules and administration, as well as other aspects of Bangladesh's past and present.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Entries on topics after 1947 are restricted to the geographical region of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] However, for biographical entries, the linguistic identity prevails.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The range of topics covered by *Banglapedia* includes political geography, religion, literature, art and architecture, folk practices and institutions, indigenous and colonial administration, politics, society, economy, ethnicity, and the sciences.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] All 64 districts of Bangladesh, as well as 451 upazilas, have been described in details ranging from topographical accounts to the number of dairy farms and hatcheries.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Over 2,000 single and four-colour illustrations depict Bangladeshi art and architecture, everyday life, cities and villages and personages.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] It has about 2,100 cross-references, cartographic information, tables and statistics.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] It is laid out in alphabetical order and is prefaced by an essay by the chief editor.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] There is a section explaining how to use the *Banglapedia*, which clarifies issues such as date systems, contributors, cross references, and headings.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] According to the publisher, the goal of this reference tool is to inquire, interpret and integrate the lived experiences and achievements of the people of Bangladesh from ancient times to the present.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The project, conceptually and territorially, interprets the term "Bangladesh" to mean successively ancient Eastern India, the Bengal Sultanate, Bengal Subah, Bengal Presidency, East Bengal, East Pakistan, and Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Over 1,200 writers and specialists contributed to the encyclopedia, one fifth of whom were foreign experts in Bangladesh or experts working abroad.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] They are mostly academics, as well as specialists in districts and upazilas for locality inputs and people from professions and occupations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] District and upazila cartography has been processed at the Geographic information system (GIS) and cartographic laboratory set up for the Banglapedia.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A gazetteer group was created to focus on districts and upazilas.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The fact that around 400 local intellectuals were charged with writing about their respective zilas and upazilas was described as a unique approach to information gathering.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] In addition, 250 people worked in research management for seven years.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A total of 2,000 scholars and technicians were involved.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] There were 270 full-time personnel on the project in all, with 35 to 40 people employed at any given time.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Sirajul Islam is the chairman of the Board of Editors of *Banglapedia*, and the editor of the Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A professor of history at the University of Dhaka, the oldest and largest university in Bangladesh, Islam gave up his day job five years before the formal date for retirement, to make time for *Banglapedia*.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] He also edited the 3 volumes of the *History of Bangladesh* (political, economic and socio-cultural), published by the Asiatic Society In 1991.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] He is now working on the *Children's Banglapedia* and the *Cultural Survey of Bangladesh*, and is also in charge of the *National Online Biography* project of the Society and the Banglapedia Trust.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The encyclopedia was prepared by a board of editors that included Professor Sirajul Islam of the Department of History, Dhaka University, as the chairman and chief editor, Professor Sajahan Miah of the Department of Philosophy, Dhaka University, as the convenor and managing editor, Professor M.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The management structure includes a total of sixty members, divided into six different sub-committees headed by six subject editors.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Each sub-committee covered a particular discipline.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] There were six consulting editors, four language editors, and three translation editors.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Each subject editor received assistance from six assistant and associate editors.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] *Banglapedia*s subject editors were: Professor Abdul Momin Chowdhury (History and Heritage), Professor Wakil Ahmed (Arts, Humanities, Religion), Professor Mahfuzur Rahman (Society and Economy), Dr Kamal Siddiqui (State and Governance), and Professor S M H Kabir (Science and Technology).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The CD-ROM version of *Banglapedia* has more entries than the print version, along with 65 video clips, 49 audio clips, 2,714 images and thumbnails, and 647 maps.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The audio clips include songs by Rabindranath Tagore and Kazi Nazrul Islam, while the video clips include Sheikh Mujibur Rahman's speech on 7 March 1971.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Some images that appear in black and white in the print version are in color in the CD-ROM version.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Designed to run on Windows 98, Windows ME, Windows 2000 and Windows NT, the CD-ROM version includes about 70,000 links and an option to create a personal "favorite list".
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Controversy over *Banglapedia* broke out even before publication, when the Inqilab group, a major Bangladeshi newspaper publishing house, got hold of a few entries on religion and related issues.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] There have also been complaints about an omission of Jamaat-e-Islami's activities during the Bangladesh Liberation War.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] A study by Bdnews24.com, a news portal, claimed that *Banglapedia* is biased and inaccurate about Bangladesh's indigenous population.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] The encyclopedia is also reported to have used derogatory coinage such as *Mogh* for Marma and Rakhine, *Tipra* for Tripuri and *Murang* for Mros, as well as *upajati* (literally "sub-nation", used to mean "tribal") to define them all.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Leaders of the indigenous community, including Chittagong Hill Tracts Regional Council member and Parbattya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samiti leader Rupayan Dewan and general secretary of Adivasi Forum Sanjib Drong, have endorsed the study's findings.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/banglapedia] Chief editor Islam acknowledged the complaint and promised to amend the second edition accordingly.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In measurement technology and metrology, **calibration** is the comparison of measurement values delivered by a device under test with those of a calibration standard of known accuracy.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Such a standard could be another measurement device of known accuracy, a device generating the quantity to be measured such as a voltage, a sound tone, or a physical artifact, such as a meter ruler.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Strictly speaking, the term "calibration" means just the act of comparison and does not include any subsequent adjustment.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The calibration standard is normally traceable to a national or international standard held by a metrology body.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This definition states that the calibration process is purely a comparison, but introduces the concept of measurement uncertainty in relating the accuracies of the device under test and the standard.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The increasing need for known accuracy and uncertainty and the need to have consistent and comparable standards internationally has led to the establishment of national laboratories.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In many countries a National Metrology Institute (NMI) will exist which will maintain primary standards of measurement (the main SI units plus a number of derived units) which will be used to provide traceability to customer's instruments by calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The NMI supports the metrological infrastructure in that country (and often others) by establishing an unbroken chain, from the top level of standards to an instrument used for measurement.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Examples of National Metrology Institutes are NPL in the UK, NIST in the United States, PTB in Germany and many others.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] To improve the quality of the calibration and have the results accepted by outside organizations it is desirable for the calibration and subsequent measurements to be "traceable" to the internationally defined measurement units.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Establishing traceability is accomplished by a formal comparison to a standard which is directly or indirectly related to national standards (such as NIST in the USA), international standards, or certified reference materials.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This may be done by national standards laboratories operated by the government or by private firms offering metrology services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Quality management systems call for an effective metrology system which includes formal, periodic, and documented calibration of all measuring instruments.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] ISO 9000 and ISO 17025 standards require that these traceable actions are to a high level and set out how they can be quantified.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] To communicate the quality of a calibration the calibration value is often accompanied by a traceable uncertainty statement to a stated confidence level.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This is evaluated through careful uncertainty analysis.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Some times a DFS (Departure From Spec) is required to operate machinery in a degraded state.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Whenever this does happen, it must be in writing and authorized by a manager with the technical assistance of a calibration technician.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Measuring devices and instruments are categorized according to the physical quantities they are designed to measure.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] These vary internationally, e.g., NIST 150-2G in the U.S. and NABL-141 in India.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The standard instrument for each test device varies accordingly, e.g., a dead weight tester for pressure gauge calibration and a dry block temperature tester for temperature gauge calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In general use, calibration is often regarded as including the process of **adjusting** the output or indication on a measurement instrument to agree with value of the applied standard, within a specified accuracy.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] For example, a thermometer could be calibrated so the error of indication or the correction is determined, and adjusted (e.g. via calibration constants) so that it shows the true temperature in Celsius at specific points on the scale.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This is the perception of the instrument's end-user.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] However, very few instruments can be adjusted to exactly match the standards they are compared to.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] For the vast majority of calibrations, the calibration process is actually the comparison of an unknown to a known and recording the results.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The calibration process begins with the design of the measuring instrument that needs to be calibrated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The design has to be able to "hold a calibration" through its calibration interval.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In other words, the design has to be capable of measurements that are "within engineering tolerance" when used within the stated environmental conditions over some reasonable period of time.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Having a design with these characteristics increases the likelihood of the actual measuring instruments performing as expected.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Basically, the purpose of calibration is for maintaining the quality of measurement as well as to ensure the proper working of particular instrument.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The exact mechanism for assigning tolerance values varies by country and as per the industry type.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The measuring equipment manufacturer generally assigns the measurement tolerance, suggests a calibration interval (CI) and specifies the environmental range of use and storage.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The using organization generally assigns the actual calibration interval, which is dependent on this specific measuring equipment's likely usage level.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The assignment of calibration intervals can be a formal process based on the results of previous calibrations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] "A calibration certificate (or calibration label) shall not contain any recommendation on the calibration interval except where this has been agreed with the customer.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The next step is defining the calibration process.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The selection of a standard or standards is the most visible part of the calibration process.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Ideally, the standard has less than 1/4 of the measurement uncertainty of the device being calibrated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] When this goal is met, the accumulated measurement uncertainty of all of the standards involved is considered to be insignificant when the final measurement is also made with the 4:1 ratio.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This ratio was probably first formalized in Handbook 52 that accompanied MIL-STD-45662A, an early US Department of Defense metrology program specification.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] It was 10:1 from its inception in the 1950s until the 1970s, when advancing technology made 10:1 impossible for most electronic measurements.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Maintaining a 4:1 accuracy ratio with modern equipment is difficult.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The test equipment being calibrated can be just as accurate as the working standard.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] If the accuracy ratio is less than 4:1, then the calibration tolerance can be reduced to compensate.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] When 1:1 is reached, only an exact match between the standard and the device being calibrated is a completely correct calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Another common method for dealing with this capability mismatch is to reduce the accuracy of the device being calibrated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] For example, a gauge with 3% manufacturer-stated accuracy can be changed to 4% so that a 1% accuracy standard can be used at 4:1.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] If the gauge is used in an application requiring 16% accuracy, having the gauge accuracy reduced to 4% will not affect the accuracy of the final measurements.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] But if the final measurement requires 10% accuracy, then the 3% gauge never can be better than 3.3:1.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Then perhaps adjusting the calibration tolerance for the gauge would be a better solution.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] If the calibration is performed at 100 units, the 1% standard would actually be anywhere between 99 and 101 units.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The acceptable values of calibrations where the test equipment is at the 4:1 ratio would be 96 to 104 units, inclusive.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Changing the acceptable range to 97 to 103 units would remove the potential contribution of all of the standards and preserve a 3.3:1 ratio.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Continuing, a further change to the acceptable range to 98 to 102 restores more than a 4:1 final ratio.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The mathematics of the example can be challenged.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] It is important that whatever thinking guided this process in an actual calibration be recorded and accessible.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Informality contributes to tolerance stacks and other difficult to diagnose post calibration problems.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Also in the example above, ideally the calibration value of 100 units would be the best point in the gauge's range to perform a single-point calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] It may be the manufacturer's recommendation or it may be the way similar devices are already being calibrated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Multiple point calibrations are also used.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Depending on the device, a zero unit state, the absence of the phenomenon being measured, may also be a calibration point.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Or zero may be resettable by the user-there are several variations possible.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Again, the points to use during calibration should be recorded.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] There may be specific connection techniques between the standard and the device being calibrated that may influence the calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] For example, in electronic calibrations involving analog phenomena, the impedance of the cable connections can directly influence the result.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Calibration methods for modern devices can be manual or automatic.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] As an example, a manual process may be used for calibration of a pressure gauge.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The procedure requires multiple steps, to connect the gauge under test to a reference master gauge and an adjustable pressure source, to apply fluid pressure to both reference and test gauges at definite points over the span of the gauge, and to compare the readings of the two.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The gauge under test may be adjusted to ensure its zero point and response to pressure comply as closely as possible to the intended accuracy.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Each step of the process requires manual record keeping.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] An automatic pressure calibrator is a device that combines an electronic control unit, a pressure intensifier used to compress a gas such as Nitrogen, a pressure transducer used to detect desired levels in a hydraulic accumulator, and accessories such as liquid traps and gauge fittings.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] An automatic system may also include data collection facilities to automate the gathering of data for record keeping.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] All of the information above is collected in a calibration procedure, which is a specific test method.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] These procedures capture all of the steps needed to perform a successful calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The manufacturer may provide one or the organization may prepare one that also captures all of the organization's other requirements.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] There are clearinghouses for calibration procedures such as the Government-Industry Data Exchange Program (GIDEP) in the United States.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This exact process is repeated for each of the standards used until transfer standards, certified reference materials and/or natural physical constants, the measurement standards with the least uncertainty in the laboratory, are reached.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This establishes the traceability of the calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] See Metrology for other factors that are considered during calibration process development.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] After all of this, individual instruments of the specific type discussed above can finally be calibrated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The process generally begins with a basic damage check.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Some organizations such as nuclear power plants collect "as-found" calibration data before any routine maintenance is performed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] After routine maintenance and deficiencies detected during calibration are addressed, an "as-left" calibration is performed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] More commonly, a calibration technician is entrusted with the entire process and signs the calibration certificate, which documents the completion of a successful calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The basic process outlined above is a difficult and expensive challenge.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The cost for ordinary equipment support is generally about 10% of the original purchase price on a yearly basis, as a commonly accepted rule-of-thumb.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Exotic devices such as scanning electron microscopes, gas chromatograph systems and laser interferometer devices can be even more costly to maintain.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The 'single measurement' device used in the basic calibration process description above does exist.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] But, depending on the organization, the majority of the devices that need calibration can have several ranges and many functionalities in a single instrument.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] A good example is a common modern oscilloscope.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] There easily could be 200,000 combinations of settings to completely calibrate and limitations on how much of an all-inclusive calibration can be automated.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] To prevent unauthorized access to an instrument tamper-proof seals are usually applied after calibration.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The picture of the oscilloscope rack shows these, and prove that the instrument has not been removed since it was last calibrated as they will possible unauthorized to the adjusting elements of the instrument.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] There also are labels showing the date of the last calibration and when the calibration interval dictates when the next one is needed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Some organizations also assign unique identification to each instrument to standardize the record keeping and keep track of accessories that are integral to a specific calibration condition.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] When the instruments being calibrated are integrated with computers, the integrated computer programs and any calibration corrections are also under control.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The words "calibrate" and "calibration" entered the English language as recently as the American Civil War, in descriptions of artillery, thought to be derived from a measurement of the calibre of a gun.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Some of the earliest known systems of measurement and calibration seem to have been created between the ancient civilizations of Egypt, Mesopotamia and the Indus Valley, with excavations revealing the use of angular gradations for construction.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The term "calibration" was likely first associated with the precise division of linear distance and angles using a dividing engine and the measurement of gravitational mass using a weighing scale.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] These two forms of measurement alone and their direct derivatives supported nearly all commerce and technology development from the earliest civilizations until about AD 1800.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Early measurement devices were *direct*, i.e. they had the same units as the quantity being measured.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Examples include length using a yardstick and mass using a weighing scale.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] At the beginning of the twelfth century, during the reign of Henry I (1100-1135), it was decreed that a yard be "the distance from the tip of the King's nose to the end of his outstretched thumb." However, it wasn't until the reign of Richard I (1197) that we find documented evidence.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Other standardization attempts followed, such as the Magna Carta (1225) for liquid measures, until the Mètre des Archives from France and the establishment of the Metric system.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] One of the earliest pressure measurement devices was the Mercury barometer, credited to Torricelli (1643), which read atmospheric pressure using Mercury.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Soon after, water-filled manometers were designed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] All these would have linear calibrations using gravimetric principles, where the difference in levels was proportional to pressure.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The normal units of measure would be the convenient inches of mercury or water.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In the direct reading hydrostatic manometer design on the left, applied pressure Pa pushes the liquid down the right side of the manometer U-tube, while a length scale next to the tube measures the difference of levels.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The resulting height difference "H" is a direct measurement of the pressure or vacuum with respect to atmospheric pressure.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In the absence of differential pressure both levels would be equal, and this would be used as the zero point.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The Industrial Revolution saw the adoption of "indirect" pressure measuring devices, which were more practical than the manometer.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] An example is in high pressure (up to 50 psi) steam engines, where mercury was used to reduce the scale length to about 60 inches, but such a manometer was expensive and prone to damage.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This stimulated the development of indirect reading instruments, of which the Bourdon tube invented by Eugène Bourdon is a notable example.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] Indirect reading design showing a Bourdon tube from the front (left) and the rear (right).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] In the front and back views of a Bourdon gauge on the right, applied pressure at the bottom fitting reduces the curl on the flattened pipe proportionally to pressure.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] This moves the free end of the tube which is linked to the pointer.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] The instrument would be calibrated against a manometer, which would be the calibration standard.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] For measurement of indirect quantities of pressure per unit area, the calibration uncertainty would be dependent on the density of the manometer fluid, and the means of measuring the height difference.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/calibration] From this other units such as pounds per square inch could be inferred and marked on the scale.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The standards to which the product is held are stipulated by the owner of the certification mark.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] 3. certifying that the manufacturer has met certain standards or belong to a certain organization or union (e.g., "union made" in clothing).
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The term "certification mark" is very recent, so while discussing historical certification marks, terms "guild sign", "quality mark", "hallmark", and "trade mark" are used by researchers.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] A certification mark indicates a property standard or regulation and a claim that the manufacturer has verified compliance with those standards or regulations.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The specific specification, test methods, and frequency of testing are published by the standards organization.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Certification listing does not necessarily guarantee fitness-for-use.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Validation testing, proper usage, and field testing are often needed.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Certification marks can be owned by independent companies absolutely unrelated in ownership to the companies, offering goods or rendering services under the particular certification mark.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The USPTO states that a certification mark is "a type of trademark".
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] However, what is meant by a collective trade marks or certification mark differs from country to country.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] However, a common feature of these types of marks is that they may be used by more than one person, as long as the users comply with the regulations of use or standards established by the holder.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Those regulations or standards may require that the mark be used only in connection with goods that have a particular geographical origin or specific characteristics.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] In some jurisdictions, the main difference between collective marks and certification marks is that the former may only be used by members of an association, while certification marks may be used by anyone who complies with the standards defined by the holder of the mark.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The holder, which may be a private or a public entity, acts as a certifier verifying that the mark is used according to established standards.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Generally, the holder of a certification mark does not itself have the right to use the mark.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] For various reasons, usually relating to technical issues, certification marks are difficult to register, especially in relation to services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] One practical workaround for trademark owners is to register the mark as an ordinary trademark in relation to quality control and similar services.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Certification is often mistakenly referred to as an *approval*, which is not true.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Organizations such as Underwriters Laboratories, TÜV Rheinland, NTA Inc, and CSA International will test the products according to standard procedures and "list" them as compliant to that standard.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] They do not *approve* anything except the use of the mark to show that a product has been certified for compliance with such specific standard.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Thus, for instance, a product certification mark for a fire door or for a spray fireproofing product does not signify its universal acceptance for use within a building.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Approvals are up to the Authority Having Jurisdiction (AHJ), such as a municipal building inspector or fire prevention officer.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] The main purpose of the regulations is to protect consumers against misleading practices.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Many jurisdictions have been required to amend their trade mark legislation to accommodate protection of certification marks under the TRIPs treaty.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] Some jurisdictions recognise certification marks from other jurisdictions.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] This means good manufactured in one country may need not go through certification in another.
[src:bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution/certification-mark] One example is the European Union recognition of Australia and New Zealand marks based on an International treaty.
